The most relevant structures are the 'simplest complexity-covering structures'.
When these structures fail, applying the simple interface structures like "relevant variation" structures in a relevant direction like "specificity" is useful, indicating that these structures dont have a limit on their relevance, as they'll always represent the limits of other variation, so when one direction of relevance is useless, applying other directions of relevance can be limitlessly useful (so connecting back to these core structures that act like limits of relevant variation is always useful and can be regularly applied in interface queries.
A graph indicating this fact is a solution to the problemÂ of 'graphing prioritized relevant structures without removing core structures that are useful, in a way that organizes/optimizes relevant queries'.
Another useful graph would indicate the similarities between relevant structures in a way that trivially connects them (like by showing how each type of structure can generate/filter the others).
